Online/UPI payment fraud is a common cybercrime where fraudsters
trick individuals into transferring money through digital payment
platforms. One realistic scenario involves a scammer posing as a
bank representative or customer support agent.
First, the fraudster contacts the victim through a phone call, SMS, or
social media, claiming there is an issue with their bank account or
offering a reward or refund. Next, they build trust and urgency,
convincing the victim to act quickly. The scammer then asks the victim
to share sensitive details such as OTPs (One-Time Passwords), UPI
PINs, or to click on a malicious link. In some cases, they send a
“collect request” on UPI apps and trick the victim into approving it,
believing they will receive money instead. Once the victim authorizes
the transaction, money is instantly transferred to the fraudster’s
account.
Such scams usually target students, elderly people, and individuals
unfamiliar with digital payments. The consequences include financial
loss, emotional stress, and sometimes leakage of personal data.
This crime can be prevented by never sharing OTPs or PINs, verifying
unknown callers, and carefully checking UPI requests before
approving them. Awareness and cautious digital behavior are key to
avoiding such frauds.

